Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My intuition stems from a critical gap in current approaches to learning textual relation embeddings: while global co-occurrence statistics between textual and knowledge base (KB) relations provide valuable supervision signals, they are typically treated as deterministic or point estimates, ignoring uncertainty inherent in both text extraction and KB alignment. Moreover, existing methods often learn static embeddings without modeling the generative process of how textual realizations emerge from underlying semantic relations. By contrast, probabilistic generation models offer a principled framework to model this mapping under uncertainty. I propose integrating global co-occurrence statistics not merely as training labels but as evidence to guide a latent-variable generative model that learns to simulate how KB relations give rise to diverse textual expressions. This approach leverages the structural richness of KBs—such as relation hierarchies and logical constraints—to regularize the embedding space, while using co-occurrence frequencies to infer posterior distributions over possible alignments. Unlike Paper 1, which uses co-occurrence for direct supervision in a discriminative setup, my idea treats it as soft evidence in a generative Bayesian framework. Compared to Paper 2, which fuses lexical features post-hoc, my method integrates structure at the modeling level. And unlike Paper 3, which distills knowledge via templates and fine-tuning, I focus on unsupervised induction of relational semantics through probabilistic generation. The novelty lies in combining global statistics with structured priors in a unified generative architecture, enabling better generalization, interpretability, and robustness to noise.

